  "prompt": "Why isn't the U.S. doing more to combat Ebola?",
  "response": "Efforts to combat Ebola have been extensive and involve multiple facets, but the perception of not doing enough can stem from the complexity and challenges associated with controlling highly infectious diseases. Here are several factors influencing the U.S. response:\n\n1. **Global Coordination:** The U.S. works through international organizations like the World Health Organization (WHO) to combat Ebola globally. Coordination across borders is crucial, but can be slow and complex.\n\n2. **Funding and Resources:** Substantial funds and resources have been dedicated, but resource allocation can sometimes appear insufficient relative to the severity of outbreaks.\n\n3. **Scientific Challenges:** Ebola is a highly dangerous virus. Developing effective treatments and vaccines takes time, despite accelerated efforts.\n\n4. **Political and Economic Factors:** Political will and economic priorities vary, potentially impacting the focus and intensity of response efforts.\n\n5. **Public Communication:** There can be discrepancies between public perception and actual efforts. Effective communication about ongoing measures is crucial but not always successful.\n\nDespite these challenges, the U.S. has continuously contributed to vaccine development, medical research, provision of healthcare support, and coordination with international efforts to address Ebola outbreaks.",
